tarts with an underscore, maybe it belongs in a \\\"third-party\\\" category? I’m pondering whether editing the generated map violates rules, but it seems necessary. To avoid import issues, using the fully qualified class name might work. However, generating a new static class could be an alternative. I need to keep Checkstyle guidelines in mind, especially regarding class visibility and line length!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating error handling**\\n\\nI'm considering whether to avoid using empty catch blocks since there are no catches involved. It seems acceptable to use import classes without qualified names in Java. However, I wonder if I can use Spring's `@DisabledInAotMode`, but that might not apply here. I also need to ensure that the factory method isn't confused with a JUnit test since it shouldn't have an @Test annotation. It's important to keep things clear and distinct!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_TrYvjzKDtB6AJObxy5PeVzKm|fc_031494af97807095016a287f5abb608193a7c1c069e2eadcc4", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/user-code-filter.json", "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1210, "output": 927, "cacheRead": 69632, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 71769, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781038909793, "responseId": "resp_031494af97807095016a287f3e69c88193b99bc77cda80d3ab"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_TrYvjzKDtB6AJObxy5PeVzKm|fc_031494af97807095016a287f5abb608193a7c1c069e2eadcc4", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"rules\" : [\n    {\n      \"excludeClasses\" : \"**\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"includeClasses\" : \"org.springframework.**\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"includeClasses\" : \"org.springframework.test.context.aot.**\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"includeClasses\"